<section xml:id="C4.S12">
<title>Generalized Logarithms and Exponentials</title>         
<para xml:id="C4.S12.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="1" xml:id="C4.S12.p1.s1">
A generalized exponential function <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p1.m1">\phi(x)</Math> satisfies the equations <Math equation-number="4.12.1" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S12.E1">\phi(x+1)=e^{\phi(x)}, if -1&lt;x&lt;\infty,</Math> , <Math equation-number="4.12.2" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S12.E2">\phi(0)=0,</Math> and is strictly increasing when <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p1.m2">0\leq x\leq 1</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="2" xml:id="C4.S12.p1.s2">
Its inverse <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p1.m3">\psi(x)</Math> is called a generalized logarithm.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C4.S12.p1.s3">
It, too, is strictly increasing when <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p1.m4">0\leq x\leq 1</Math> , and <Math equation-number="4.12.3" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S12.E3">\psi(e^{x})=1+\psi(x), if -\infty&lt;x&lt;\infty,</Math> , <Math equation-number="4.12.4" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S12.E4">\psi(0)=0</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C4.S12.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.s1">
These functions are not unique.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.s2">
The simplest choice is given by <Math equation-number="4.12.5" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S12.E5">\phi(x)=\psi(x)=x, if 0\leq x\leq 1</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.s3">
Then <Math equation-number="4.12.6" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S12.E6">\phi(x)=\ln\left(x+1\right), if -1&lt;x&lt;0,</Math> and <Math equation-number="4.12.7" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S12.E7">\phi(x)=\exp\exp\cdots\exp\left(x-\left\lfloor x\right\rfloor\right), if x&gt;1,</Math> where the exponentiations are carried out <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.m1">\left\lfloor x\right\rfloor</Math> times.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="4" sentence-num-in-section="7" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.s4">
Correspondingly, <Math equation-number="4.12.8" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S12.E8">\psi(x)=e^{x}-1, if -\infty&lt;x&lt;0,</Math> and <Math equation-number="4.12.9" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S12.E9">\psi(x)=\ell+{\ln^{(\ell)}}x, if x&gt;1,</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.m2">{\ln^{(\ell)}}x</Math> denotes the <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.m3">\ell</Math> -th repeated logarithm of <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.m4">x</Math> , and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.m5">\ell</Math> is the positive integer determined by the condition <Math equation-number="4.12.10" mode="display" xml:id="C4.S12.E10">0\leq{\ln^{(\ell)}}x&lt;1.</Math>
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="5" sentence-num-in-section="8" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.s5">
Both <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.m6">\phi(x)</Math> and <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p2.m7">\psi(x)</Math> are continuously differentiable.
</sentence>

</para>
 
<para xml:id="C4.S12.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="9" xml:id="C4.S12.p3.s1">
For further information, see Clenshaw et al. (1986).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="10" xml:id="C4.S12.p3.s2">
For <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C4.S12.p3.m1">C^{\infty}</Math> generalized logarithms, see Walker (1991).
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="11" xml:id="C4.S12.p3.s3">
For analytic generalized logarithms, see Kneser (1950).
</sentence>

</para>
 
</section>
